The poet's grateful acknowledgment to his Muses

‘ He on whom thou dost look with kindly eye in his natal hour, Mela pomene, is set apart from the pursuit of common glories. He shall not win renown as athlete or as general. But the quiet groves and streams shall be his haunts and he shall gain his farne through poesy (1-12). So through thy gift am Ι counted to-day a lyric bard and Envy’s tooth is dulled. All my fame, my inspiration, and my power to please are thine, sweet Muse (13-24).'

The publication of his three books of odes in 23 Bc. had established Horace's name as a lyric poet, and his appointment in 17 ΒΕ. to write the Carmen Saeculare had officially fixed his position.
